title: For Sale/Trade:  Winchester model 94 30/30
postcontent: The classic Winchester model 94 lever action.  This model dates to 1979. Most Winchester folks say pre 64 guns are the most desirable.  In 1964, Winchester changed many  items in their guns to save costs.  By the late 70s, Winchester listened to their customers and addressed many of the complaints (better wood, machined internal parts, and darker blueing).  Guns over the next years began to again change due to lawyer's (safeties and such). The late 70s Winchesters are considered the best value for use due to their quality and construction.  This gun does have a minimal round count, but because of long term storage without intervention, there is some flaws in the receiver blueing (typical of post 63 Winchesters due to metallurgy).  Blueing on the barrel is perfect.  The walnut has a very nice color and grain. This would be a great gun for someone who wants a low use gun which would be great in the woods or field.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Walther P-22
postcontent: This is a first gen Walther P-22 target model (without the newer-styled rubberized grip) with the 5” barrel.  It includes the box, all of the proprietary tools, extra magazine, extra front sights, and the extra grip insert.  The additional mass, from the longer 1.6” barrel and 3.4 ounces added to the muzzle end (beyond the traditional length of the standard P-22) does lend stability to its hold and aim, especially at extended ranges.  Some .22LR pistols choke on bulk ammo (Sig mosquito, ISSC, etc.), but Walther pistols chug right along.  Its reliability reminds you of a glock - if a Walther P-22 won't feed it, you probably shouldn't buy it or shoot it.Walther P-22 owners appreciate true versitility, since there are more after-market options (lasers, lights, other rail attachments, grip-swell inserts, front-sight replacements, barrels, threaded-muzzle attachment/devices and holsters) available to a P-22 than any other modern rimfire pistol made today - basically, it is the 10/22 of rimfire pistols.Walther no longer makes the original-gripped model (kind of like the Gen 4 Glock is replacing the Gen 3), and now produces a newer model with a rubberized grip.  I have nothing bad to say about rubberized grips - they have their place.  They do an excellent job of taming recoil and ensuring a good positive grip, but this is a .22 LR we are talking about.  Recoil really isn't an issue.  Those who would rather have the original style might want to consider picking one up before they become less common and more expensive.  EXTRA:  Saiga 12 magazines - (3) factory 5-round, still inside the wrapper, and (2) AGP Arms Inc. 10-round (these are the ones that work - not Crapco).  I will sell each of the magazines for $35 a piece.EXTRA EXTRA:  Sig 229 12-round factory magazines SIX (6) total = FOUR (4) still in wrapper - $30 each, and TWO (2) gently used - $28 each.
